{
  "id": "study-perlon-001",
  "version": "1.0",
  "title": "Perlon — The Zip Ground",
  "subtitle": "Minimal techno from Frankfurt, built for floors that never close",
  "annotation": "The Perlon aesthetic is not about what you add. It is about what you refuse to remove. The kick is four-on-the-floor without apology — hard, saturated, warm. Hats run every 16th note, slightly swung on the off-beats, darkened by heavy low-pass filtering. The snare sits on 2 and 4 with ghost notes one 16th ahead, barely audible. One anticipation kick at the end of the phrase creates forward momentum without disrupting hypnosis. The open hat lands on the + of 2 in each bar — structural, not decorative. Do not add fills. Do not add drops. The groove is the journey.",
  "grooveProfile": {
    "swingFeel": "Subtle 16th-note swing. Off-beats delayed 15-18 ticks. Mechanical but breathing — never stiff, never lazy.",
    "accentLogic": "Kick carries weight. Hat velocity alternates 2/1 on every 16th to suggest pulse without stating it. Ghost snares exist at the edge of perception.",
    "microtimingTendencies": "Two-bar loop. Groove is identical each cycle. The transformation happens through filter sweeps and textural evolution in the mix, not pattern variation."
  },
